ds.merry

Class ObjectSet<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • ds.merry.ObjectSet<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    OrderedSet

    public class ObjectSet<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<T>
    An unordered set where the keys are objects. This implementation uses linear probing with the backward-shift algorithm for removal, and finds space for keys using Fibonacci hashing instead of the more-common power-of-two mask. Null keys are not allowed. No allocation is done except when growing the table size.
    This set uses Fibonacci hashing to help distribute what may be very bad hashCode() results across the whole capacity. See Malte Skarupke's blog post for more information on Fibonacci hashing. It uses linear probing to resolve collisions, which is far from the academically optimal algorithm, but performs considerably better in practice than most alternatives, and combined with Fibonacci hashing, it can handle "normal" generated hashCode() implementations, and not just theoretically optimal hashing functions. Even if all hashCode()s this is given collide, it will still work, just slowly; the older libGDX implementation using cuckoo hashing would crash with an OutOfMemoryError with under 50 collisions.
    This map performs very fast contains and remove (typically O(1), worst case O(n) due to occasional probing, but still very fast). Add may be a bit slower, depending on hash collisions, but this data structure is somewhat collision-resistant. Load factors greater than 0.91 greatly increase the chances the set will have to rehash to the next higher POT size. Memory usage is excellent, and the aforementioned collision-resistance helps avoid too much capacity resizing.
    The backward-shift algorithm used during removal apparently is key to the good performance of this implementation, even though this doesn't use Robin Hood hashing; the performance of remove(Object) has improved considerably over the previous libGDX version.
    Iteration should be fast with OrderedSet and OrderedMap, whereas ObjectSet and ObjectMap aren't designed to provide especially quick iteration.

      • size

        public int size

      • shift

        protected int shift
        Used by place(Object) to bit-shift the upper bits of a long into a usable range (less than or equal to mask, greater than or equal to 0). If you're setting it in a subclass, this shift can be negative, which is a convenient way to match the number of bits in mask; if mask is a 7-bit number, then a shift of -7 will correctly shift the upper 7 bits into the lowest 7 positions. If using what this class sets, shift will be greater than 32 and less than 64; if you use this shift with an int, it will still correctly move the upper bits of an int to the lower bits, thanks to Java's implicit modulus on shifts.
        You can also use mask to mask the low bits of a number, which may be faster for some hashCode()s, if you reimplement place(Object).

      • mask

        protected int mask
        The bitmask used to contain hashCode()s to the indices that can be fit into the key array this uses. This should always be all-1-bits in its low positions; that is, it must be a power of two minus 1. If you subclass and change place(Object), you may want to use this instead of shift to isolate usable bits of a hash.

    • Method Detail

      • place

        protected int place(T item)
        Finds an array index between 0 and mask, both inclusive, corresponding to the hash code of item. By default, this uses "Fibonacci Hashing" on the Object.hashCode() of item; this multiplies item.hashCode() by a long constant (2 to the 64, divided by the golden ratio) and shifts the high-quality uppermost bits into the lowest positions so they can be used as array indices. The multiplication by a long may be somewhat slow on GWT, but it will be correct across all platforms and won't lose precision. Using Fibonacci Hashing allows even very poor hashCode() implementations, such as those that only differ in their upper bits, to work in a hash table without heavy collision rates. It has known problems when all or most hashCode()s are multiples of larger Fibonacci numbers; see this blog post by Malte Skarupke for more details. In the unlikely event that most of your hashCode()s are Fibonacci numbers, you can subclass this to change this method, which is a one-liner in this form: return (int) (item.hashCode() * 0x9E3779B97F4A7C15L >>> shift);
        This can be overridden by subclasses, which you may want to do if your key type needs special consideration for its hash (such as if you use arrays as keys, which still requires that the arrays are not modified). Subclasses that don't need the collision decrease of Fibonacci Hashing (assuming the key class has a good hashCode()) may do fine with a simple implementation: return (item.hashCode() & mask);
        Parameters:
        item - a key that this method will hash, by default by calling Object.hashCode() on it; non-null
        Returns:
        an int between 0 and mask, both inclusive

      • shrink

        public void shrink(int maximumCapacity)
        Reduces the size of the backing arrays to be the specified capacity or less. If the capacity is already less, nothing is done. If the set contains more items than the specified capacity, the next highest power of two capacity is used instead.

      • clear

        public void clear(int maximumCapacity)
        Clears the set and reduces the size of the backing arrays to be the specified capacity, if they are larger. The reduction is done by allocating new arrays, though for large arrays this can be faster than clearing the existing array.

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Clears the set, leaving the backing arrays at the current capacity. When the capacity is high and the population is low, iteration can be unnecessarily slow. clear(int) can be used to reduce the capacity.
